    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Christian Yelich** (72.61) and **Trea Turner** (71.43) anchoring our lineup as the top-tier plays. **Christian Yelich** benefits from a high-efficiency matchup against Littell, where his strong platoon advantage (+13%) and favorable order placement outweigh the minor park penalty. Similarly, **Trea Turner** remains an elite start despite facing a tough arm in Gallen; his leadoff role (+10%) and the scarcity value of his legs make him indispensable regardless of the opposing skill level. **Kyle Schwarber** (67.82) and **Colt Keith** (67.49) round out the high-upside core, with the latter capitalizing on a favorable matchup against Alcantara and a significant boost from the opponent's slow delivery, which optimizes his stolen base floor.\n\nStrategic optimization favored high-floor production over the speculative upside of our bench. The most difficult omission was **Jerar Encarnacion** (56.19), who narrowly missed the cut behind **Kazuma Okamoto** (58.71). While **Jerar Encarnacion** benefits from a significant 16% park factor boost, the optimizer preferred the relative stability and superior SP-xERA matchup profile of **Kazuma Okamoto**. Furthermore, we are exercising caution with **Yordan Alvarez** (55.60); although he is a premier talent, his score is currently depressed by a difficult draw against Logan Gilbert (-19% SP skill) and a pending lineup status, keeping him in the lineup but marking him as a high-risk asset compared to the pure efficiency of our middle-infield starters.\n\nOwners should monitor weather reports specifically for **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (61.24) and **Caleb Durbin** (64.76). Both players are receiving a 5\u201310% boost from favorable winds, which elevates their utility today, but that score is tethered to the assumption that those atmospheric conditions hold. While **Hyeseong Kim** (40.38) and **Victor Scott II** (55.66) offer speed, the sheer difficulty of facing elite arms like deGrom or maintaining efficiency in the #9 hole kept them on the pine. We remain committed to maximizing our game cap efficiency; if the lineup for **Josh Smith** (#8) or **Yordan Alvarez** deviates from our projections, we will be forced to re-evaluate their utilization to ensure we aren't burning limited starts on sub-optimal platoons.",
